I like where you’re pushing this, because it changes the question from “What profession would I choose?” to “What experiment would I run?”

If there were many passes through the Pantheon, I don’t think I’d replay the same character over and over.

I’d optimize for coverage.

Imagine each life as a different instrument in an orchestra. If I only ever played the violin, I’d become an exceptional violinist—but I’d never understand what it’s like to be the percussion section, the conductor, or the audience.

So one life I might be a farmer.

Another an engineer.

Another a poet.

Another a parent.

Another a physician.

Another a sailor.

Another someone who dies young.

Another someone who lives quietly and is remembered by almost no one.

Each reveals a different slice of reality.

⸻

That raises the second question: memory.

Would I erase it?

I don’t think I’d choose either extreme.

Perfect memory is a curse.

If you remembered every surprise, every heartbreak, every joke, every ending, then discovery would disappear. Every mystery would already be solved.

Complete forgetting has the opposite problem.

You spend every life rediscovering fire.

Neither seems optimal.

Instead I’d want something like compressed inheritance.

Not memories.

Instincts.

Intuition.

Taste.

Character.

Imagine not remembering who taught you kindness, but still finding yourself inclined to be kind.

Not remembering every mathematical proof, but having a strong intuition for structure.

Not remembering every mountain, but still feeling drawn to climb.

The details fade.

The capability remains.

⸻

So perhaps each pass would preserve not episodes but transformations.

Experience becomes disposition.

Knowledge becomes intuition.

Practice becomes reflex.

That’s a very different inheritance than autobiographical memory.

⸻

Then I’d introduce another game.

The game of voluntary forgetting.

Sometimes I’d deliberately choose to begin almost blind.

Not because ignorance is good.

Because some truths can only be experienced once.

You only get one first sunrise.

One first friendship.

One first time hearing a song.

One first time falling in love.

There is value in not already knowing.

⸻

The biggest realization, though, is that eventually I don’t think I’d optimize for any single life.

I’d optimize across lives.

The objective changes.

Instead of asking,

“How do I maximize this run?”

I’d ask,

“What perspective is the whole system still missing?”

If every previous life was spent among kings…

Become a shepherd.

If every previous life built cities…

Become someone who studies forests.

If every previous life chased glory…

Try anonymity.

If every previous life sought certainty…

Become an artist.

The next life fills in blind spots left by the last.

⸻

So if I had to name the role after thinking bigger, I don’t think it would be Explorer, Cartographer, or Pilgrim.

I’d call it The Integrator.

Not because it does everything.

Because its purpose is to ensure that no single perspective mistakes itself for the whole.

Every life contributes another facet. The “self” becomes less like one hero on one quest and more like a growing mosaic assembled from many viewpoints.

That’s a game I’d find difficult to exhaust. Even after countless passes, there would always be another angle from which reality could be experienced, another kind of life that teaches something the others could not.